WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.360
Hi everyone, my name is Isabella Velazquez and today we'll be walking through how to

00:00:07.360 --> 00:00:13.120
create a Streamlit app in Positron, Positron's next generation data science IDE.

00:00:13.120 --> 00:00:17.920
I will walk you through setting up your project and your Python environment in Positron, how

00:00:17.920 --> 00:00:23.200
to build your app with the help of the integrated viewer, how to get assistance from large language

00:00:23.200 --> 00:00:28.799
models through Positron Assistant, and finally how to deploy and share your apps with others.

00:00:28.799 --> 00:00:31.120
So with that, let's get started.

00:00:31.120 --> 00:00:33.040
Here we have Positron open.

00:00:33.040 --> 00:00:38.200
If you do not have Positron and Python installed, we have recommended instructions linked in

00:00:38.200 --> 00:00:40.680
the description below.

00:00:40.680 --> 00:00:45.180
You have the option of opening an existing folder or creating a new one.

00:00:45.180 --> 00:00:49.200
In this case, I'm going to click New from Git.

00:00:49.200 --> 00:00:53.560
Then I'm going to paste the Git repository URL of our project.

00:00:53.560 --> 00:00:58.959
You can choose your desired directory and then click OK.

00:00:58.959 --> 00:01:05.400
What this does is it clones the GitHub repository and then opens up the folder where the files

00:01:05.400 --> 00:01:06.599
live.

00:01:06.599 --> 00:01:12.519
On the left hand side, you can see the activity bar and you can see the project files in the

00:01:12.519 --> 00:01:16.279
file explorer, which you can view and open.

00:01:16.279 --> 00:01:24.879
Let's open up original-app.py, which is a project that we'll be working on today.

00:01:24.879 --> 00:01:29.120
Because we're working in Python, let's now set up our environment.

00:01:29.120 --> 00:01:33.279
There are various different ways of doing this, but for today's example, we're going

00:01:33.279 --> 00:01:40.559
to be using UV, which is an extremely fast package and project manager written in Rust.

00:01:40.559 --> 00:01:46.720
I'm going to open up my terminal.

00:01:46.720 --> 00:01:54.400
You can see the console on the left and then terminal on the right.

00:01:54.400 --> 00:02:00.680
Clicking on Terminal opens up a new terminal and then I can run the snippet to create the

00:02:00.680 --> 00:02:05.440
virtual environment, uv-map.

00:02:05.440 --> 00:02:10.720
Now I have a new virtual environment and notice the notification that asks, we notice

00:02:10.720 --> 00:02:12.759
a new environment has been created.

00:02:12.759 --> 00:02:16.839
Do you want to select it for the workspace folder?

00:02:16.839 --> 00:02:18.240
Going to hit yes.

00:02:18.240 --> 00:02:22.880
Now both the console and the new terminals will reflect the new project specific virtual

00:02:22.880 --> 00:02:23.880
environment.

00:02:23.880 --> 00:02:29.199
Next, I'm going to install all of the project dependencies by returning to my terminal and

00:02:29.199 --> 00:02:39.279
then typing source.vimp.bin.activate.

00:02:39.279 --> 00:02:50.320
And now I'm going to install them by running uv pip install-r requirements.txt.

00:02:50.320 --> 00:02:55.199
If you noticed, all of the packages installed super quickly and now we're ready to start

00:02:55.199 --> 00:02:56.199
building.

00:02:56.199 --> 00:03:00.039
This code is actually for a Streamlit app that I created several years ago when I was

00:03:00.039 --> 00:03:02.279
very new to Streamlit.

00:03:02.279 --> 00:03:08.960
This is an example using trauma hospital analytics from the US and it visualizes hospital locations

00:03:08.960 --> 00:03:15.720
and analyzes geographic accessibility based on Kyle Walker's tutorial.

00:03:15.720 --> 00:03:17.839
Let's look at the different sections.

00:03:17.839 --> 00:03:23.960
The initial lines of code import necessary libraries such as pandas and numpy, matplotlib

00:03:23.960 --> 00:03:30.600
and seaborn, geopandas, and of course, Streamlit.

00:03:30.600 --> 00:03:37.639
The next part configures the Streamlit page and also adds a title and a caption.

00:03:37.639 --> 00:03:41.320
The next section handles the user input and data retrieval.

00:03:41.320 --> 00:03:45.479
ST sidebar creates a sidebar on the web page for user controls.

00:03:45.479 --> 00:03:51.039
ST select box creates a drop-down menu in the sidebar which allows the user to select

00:03:51.119 --> 00:03:56.440
one of three states, California, Arizona, or Wisconsin, and the selected value is stored

00:03:56.440 --> 00:03:59.000
in the state variable.

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:01.440
Cache data is a Streamlit caching decorator.

00:04:01.440 --> 00:04:06.679
It tells Streamlit to run the function below only once for a given set of inputs and that

00:04:06.679 --> 00:04:11.399
the function is called again with the same inputs of retrieve the cache result instead

00:04:11.399 --> 00:04:15.720
of rerunning the function which saves time.

00:04:15.720 --> 00:04:21.320
Set data uses Pygris to download census track data for the selected state.

00:04:21.320 --> 00:04:29.959
Load data reads a GeoJSON file named trauma.GeoJSON which contains the trauma hospital locations.

00:04:29.959 --> 00:04:35.399
It then filters this data to include only the hospital in the selected data frame and

00:04:35.399 --> 00:04:39.480
returns the filtered geo data frame.

00:04:40.440 --> 00:04:45.959
Finally, this part of the code structures the app's layout and performs the core geospatial

00:04:45.959 --> 00:04:47.440
analysis.

00:04:47.440 --> 00:04:55.359
ST columns divides the main content area into two columns and then with column defines the

00:04:55.359 --> 00:04:58.279
content to be placed in each column.

00:04:58.279 --> 00:05:04.160
In the first column, the display is an interactive map using the trauma geo data frame showing

00:05:04.160 --> 00:05:07.420
the locations of the trauma hospitals.

00:05:07.420 --> 00:05:12.019
In the second column, there is a table with specific columns of the raw trauma hospital

00:05:12.019 --> 00:05:17.980
data and then also a bar chart of the histogram data visualizing the distribution and minimum

00:05:17.980 --> 00:05:24.540
distances from the census tracks to trauma centers.

00:05:24.540 --> 00:05:28.059
Let's say we want to take a closer look at the data that we're actually visualizing in

00:05:28.059 --> 00:05:29.500
the dashboard.

00:05:29.500 --> 00:05:35.700
We could open it up here in the file explorer, but this is a JSON file and a bit difficult

00:05:35.820 --> 00:05:37.859
to read.

00:05:37.859 --> 00:05:48.820
Let's instead open up our console and then here I'm going to type in import geopandas

00:05:48.820 --> 00:06:02.899
as GP and then trauma equals GP.feed file trauma.geojson.

00:06:02.899 --> 00:06:09.660
Doing this populates the data in Positron's data explorer.

00:06:09.660 --> 00:06:15.339
If I open it up, I can get a closer look at what's contained within the geojson file.

00:06:15.339 --> 00:06:19.260
I can see the names of the individual variables.

00:06:19.260 --> 00:06:27.779
If I click on this arrow, I can see the specific details or values of those variables.

00:06:28.019 --> 00:06:34.380
For example, here are the names of the various hospitals.

00:06:34.380 --> 00:06:39.380
We have other information like their address and telephone number.

00:06:39.380 --> 00:06:44.500
We also have some quantitative data.

00:06:44.500 --> 00:06:51.660
For example, population and I can click on here to get a closer look at what that looks

00:06:51.660 --> 00:06:52.660
like.

00:06:52.700 --> 00:06:58.260
I can take a quick look, sort ascending, see that there's some negative values, so those

00:06:58.260 --> 00:07:01.579
need to be cleaned up, sort descending.

00:07:01.579 --> 00:07:10.339
I can also check out this viewer and see the general distribution of those values as well.

00:07:10.339 --> 00:07:18.420
Let's say I want to add a filter and I want it to say, because it's population, be greater

00:07:18.420 --> 00:07:21.019
than zero.

00:07:21.019 --> 00:07:26.500
Then I can take a closer look at the population without those negative 999 numbers, which

00:07:26.500 --> 00:07:32.980
presumably are missing or meant to be discarded in some way.

00:07:32.980 --> 00:07:36.579
Also be aware that this isn't going to change your data.

00:07:36.579 --> 00:07:41.140
It's meant to be an ephemeral view for you to get to know your data before you get started

00:07:41.140 --> 00:07:43.980
on your work.

00:07:43.980 --> 00:07:46.459
I will close out of here.

00:07:46.459 --> 00:07:51.899
Let's return to our app.

00:07:51.899 --> 00:07:56.059
Now we have everything we need to run our Streamlit app.

00:07:56.059 --> 00:08:02.100
In the original-app.py file, I can click the play button to see a preview in Positron's

00:08:02.100 --> 00:08:10.260
viewer pane.

00:08:10.260 --> 00:08:27.260
I can interact with the app directly in the viewer pane.

00:08:27.260 --> 00:08:36.219
Or I can click the pop-up button to open it in my default browser.

00:08:36.219 --> 00:08:40.340
From here, we can see the different components that we just talked about.

00:08:40.340 --> 00:08:44.539
On the left-hand side is our sidebar with our filters.

00:08:44.539 --> 00:08:50.659
And then in the main body of the dashboard, we have a title, a caption, a container with

00:08:50.659 --> 00:08:56.219
two columns, one containing an interactive map and another containing a table.

00:08:56.219 --> 00:09:01.700
And then a second container that contains the histogram with the minimum distance to

00:09:01.700 --> 00:09:05.820
trauma center from the tracked centroid.

00:09:05.820 --> 00:09:08.299
Now let's go back to Positron.

00:09:08.299 --> 00:09:14.260
You can enable live reloading by saving the script after making an edit.

00:09:14.260 --> 00:09:20.299
So let's say in the title, I'm going to add 2025.

00:09:20.299 --> 00:09:23.580
Hit save.

00:09:23.580 --> 00:09:32.979
Now you'll notice that the dashboard gives me an option to rerun and to always rerun.

00:09:32.979 --> 00:09:39.219
Saying always rerun enables automatically rerunning for the session.

00:09:39.219 --> 00:09:42.760
I'm just going to hit rerun for now.

00:09:42.760 --> 00:09:49.260
Because one neat thing about Positron is that you can configure instantaneous updates anytime

00:09:49.260 --> 00:09:51.460
you open this folder.

00:09:51.460 --> 00:09:56.619
The way to do this is to configure your streamlet config.toml file.

00:09:56.619 --> 00:10:01.940
To do this, I can open up my terminal.

00:10:01.940 --> 00:10:10.580
From here, we can open up a new terminal.

00:10:10.580 --> 00:10:18.900
I'm going to create a new folder by typing make directory-p.streamlet and then create

00:10:18.900 --> 00:10:25.299
a file by running nano.streamlet.config.toml.

00:10:25.299 --> 00:10:32.179
Here I'm going to add my settings, square braces, server, and then in a new line, run

00:10:32.179 --> 00:10:35.140
on save equals true.

00:10:35.140 --> 00:10:47.580
I'm on a Mac, so to save, I'm going to hit Control-O, Tab, and then Control-X to exit.

00:10:47.580 --> 00:10:51.940
If you notice, in the file explorer, we have a new folder called .streamlet.

00:10:51.940 --> 00:10:54.419
I'm going to open it up.

00:10:54.419 --> 00:11:00.020
Here's my config.toml file.

00:11:00.020 --> 00:11:08.099
Next I'm going to open up the command palette by running Command-Shift-P, then reload window.

00:11:08.099 --> 00:11:10.979
This actually applies to new settings.

00:11:10.979 --> 00:11:20.619
And then I can rerun my app by hitting the play button.

00:11:20.619 --> 00:11:25.419
Let's say I want to remove the year.

00:11:25.419 --> 00:11:29.260
When I hit save, the changes are automatically applied.

00:11:29.260 --> 00:11:34.260
As you can imagine, this is very helpful if you want to iterate on your dashboard and

00:11:34.260 --> 00:11:42.299
quickly see the changes without having to reload every single time.

00:11:42.299 --> 00:11:47.219
As I mentioned, I created this dashboard a few years ago, and there are a lot of improvements

00:11:47.219 --> 00:11:50.419
to the features and functionalities that we can make.

00:11:50.419 --> 00:11:57.619
Nowadays, we can do that with the help of large language models, or LLMs.

00:11:57.619 --> 00:12:02.619
Positron Assistant is a preview feature in Positron and provides LLM integration for

00:12:02.619 --> 00:12:07.179
chat with Anthropic and inline completions with GitHub Copilot.

00:12:07.179 --> 00:12:12.260
You can configure it by following the Positron Assistant documentation.

00:12:12.260 --> 00:12:17.700
Once you have it configured, you can open it from the activity bar like I just did,

00:12:17.700 --> 00:12:25.419
and Positron Assistant automatically detects app.py and other relevant environment variables.

00:12:25.419 --> 00:12:28.640
There are various ways of using Positron Assistant.

00:12:28.640 --> 00:12:34.320
You can use agent mode if you want Positron Assistant to determine the steps needed for

00:12:34.320 --> 00:12:38.340
your request and carry them out on your behalf.

00:12:38.340 --> 00:12:43.979
It can execute code, create and modify files, and identify next steps based on the results

00:12:43.979 --> 00:12:45.979
of the previous steps.

00:12:45.979 --> 00:12:50.460
For edit mode, you can make code changes with the model's help.

00:12:50.460 --> 00:12:54.780
The model will suggest code changes based on your prompts, and then you can apply those

00:12:54.780 --> 00:12:57.260
changes to your code.

00:12:57.260 --> 00:12:59.020
I like ask mode.

00:12:59.020 --> 00:13:05.020
I use this mode to ask questions, get help with debugging, or request code generation.

00:13:05.020 --> 00:13:09.859
And this is the default mode when you open the chat.

00:13:09.859 --> 00:13:14.140
Since I've reloaded Positron since the time that we read in the GeoJSON file, I want to

00:13:14.140 --> 00:13:19.859
make sure that I do that again.

00:13:19.859 --> 00:13:32.739
That way, it is populated in my variables pane, which Positron Assistant can read.

00:13:32.739 --> 00:13:35.700
I want a quick overview of key metrics for each state.

00:13:35.700 --> 00:13:44.020
So I can ask Positron Assistant, can you add a row of metrics to the dashboard using

00:13:44.020 --> 00:13:47.299
ST metric?

00:13:47.299 --> 00:14:00.059
I want number of hospitals, number of helipads, and number of level one trauma centers.

00:14:00.059 --> 00:14:06.780
They should be filtered by what is chosen in ST filter.

00:14:06.780 --> 00:14:07.780
I hit enter.

00:14:07.780 --> 00:14:10.859
You can see Positron Assistant is working.

00:14:11.219 --> 00:14:24.659
First, it's examining the trauma data set to understand what columns are available.

00:14:24.659 --> 00:14:31.260
It can see the structure of the trauma data set, and it can create the metrics I requested,

00:14:31.260 --> 00:14:35.700
number of hospitals, helipads, and level one trauma centers.

00:14:35.700 --> 00:14:42.700
And then it lets me know, here's the code to add these metrics to your dashboard.

00:14:42.700 --> 00:14:47.340
With all of the code for the Streamlit app, then it also lets me know what exactly we

00:14:47.340 --> 00:14:53.460
are adding, the metrics row, the total hospitals, and hospitals with helipad, and that it will

00:14:53.460 --> 00:14:56.659
be filtered by the state that is selected.

00:14:56.659 --> 00:15:01.559
And I can see where exactly it says add metrics row.

00:15:01.840 --> 00:15:05.080
In this case, if I want to, I have a few options.

00:15:05.080 --> 00:15:11.280
I can run in the console just to see what exactly this code entails.

00:15:11.280 --> 00:15:16.440
I also can apply in the editor.

00:15:16.440 --> 00:15:19.239
If I want to, I can insert at the cursor.

00:15:19.239 --> 00:15:28.119
If I click somewhere on my script, I can also copy, or I can insert it into a new file.

00:15:28.559 --> 00:15:33.520
This time, Positron Assistant gave me the full app that I asked for.

00:15:33.520 --> 00:15:36.320
Let's insert it into a new file.

00:15:36.320 --> 00:15:40.859
I'll have to save it as something, so let's say app2.

00:15:40.859 --> 00:15:47.479
Let's go back to our file explorer and open up app2.py.

00:15:47.479 --> 00:15:53.280
Click play.

00:15:53.280 --> 00:15:57.559
I can pop it out to make it easier to see.

00:15:57.679 --> 00:15:58.679
Here we go.

00:15:58.679 --> 00:16:06.440
Here is my updated dashboard, and I can see there is a new row with my three metrics that

00:16:06.440 --> 00:16:12.320
I requested, total hospitals, total hospitals with helipads, and level one trauma centers.

00:16:12.320 --> 00:16:19.799
I can filter, and I can see that the numbers have updated.

00:16:19.799 --> 00:16:26.200
And from here, I can keep chatting with Positron Assistant to continue making the dashboard

00:16:26.200 --> 00:16:31.880
more customized, more complex, based on my stakeholders' needs.

00:16:31.880 --> 00:16:39.000
And because it is AI, it varies slightly every single time you ask it questions.

00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:47.400
In the end, the app that I created is the one stored in app.py, which if I run it, you

00:16:47.400 --> 00:16:52.880
can take a look.

00:16:52.880 --> 00:16:55.799
This is what it looks like.

00:16:56.400 --> 00:16:59.840
It has these rows of metrics.

00:16:59.840 --> 00:17:04.599
One thing that Positron Assistant helped me with was adding all of the states, so I don't

00:17:04.599 --> 00:17:07.000
have to filter by just three.

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:13.920
It was very easy to create the vector with all of the information that I need.

00:17:13.920 --> 00:17:23.079
It also helped me add this export data option, so that if folks are interested in either

00:17:23.160 --> 00:17:29.359
the complete version of the data or summary report, they can download it here.

00:17:29.359 --> 00:17:35.599
In terms of the main dashboard, in addition to the metrics rows, Positron Assistant also

00:17:35.599 --> 00:17:42.280
helped me create a nicer looking table that can actually be searched, as well as a nicer

00:17:42.280 --> 00:17:49.199
looking histogram where I can see the number of census tracts, also the mean and medium

00:17:49.199 --> 00:17:52.000
to kind of compare them.

00:17:52.000 --> 00:17:58.079
Here's some insights on the distances.

00:17:58.079 --> 00:18:03.239
Once your Streamlit app is ready, you'll want to share it with your team or your manager

00:18:03.239 --> 00:18:04.839
or whoever is interested.

00:18:04.839 --> 00:18:10.079
There are many ways of deploying Streamlit apps, but I'm going to show you how to deploy

00:18:10.079 --> 00:18:17.280
to PositConnect, which is our enterprise publishing platform, from Positron directly through the

00:18:17.280 --> 00:18:18.280
Posit Publisher.

00:18:18.280 --> 00:18:26.040
Please note, I already have PositConnect configured for deployment, but that consisted of the

00:18:26.040 --> 00:18:32.280
PositConnect URL, the name, and the API key.

00:18:32.280 --> 00:18:43.880
Once you have the deployment configured, you can hit the Posit Publisher button.

00:18:43.880 --> 00:18:47.760
Then it's going to ask you for the title of your content.

00:18:48.239 --> 00:18:51.479
I'm going to stay with Streamlit Example.

00:18:51.479 --> 00:18:56.079
I'm going to publish it to the demo server.

00:18:56.079 --> 00:18:59.800
It's going to create a configuration file.

00:18:59.800 --> 00:19:09.040
On the left, you can see the Posit Publisher home with the project files and other information

00:19:09.040 --> 00:19:11.160
about the deployment.

00:19:11.160 --> 00:19:18.439
I'm also going to add the GeoJSON file so that it makes sure to read in the data to

00:19:18.439 --> 00:19:21.479
actually display the app.

00:19:21.479 --> 00:19:26.680
Then I'm going to hit Deploy Your Project.

00:19:26.680 --> 00:19:34.160
Now it's restoring my environment, rebuilding everything so that I can publish to PositConnect.

00:19:34.160 --> 00:19:39.160
It lets me know that deployment was successful.

00:19:39.160 --> 00:19:52.959
Now I can take a look.

00:19:52.959 --> 00:19:55.000
Now we have our deployed Streamlit app.

00:19:55.000 --> 00:19:57.640
It looks just like it did in the preview.

00:19:57.640 --> 00:20:06.199
I can use the filters.

00:20:06.199 --> 00:20:07.839
Then I can go to my settings.

00:20:07.839 --> 00:20:14.760
I can share to anybody with no login required, to all users with a login required, or specific

00:20:14.760 --> 00:20:15.760
users.

00:20:15.760 --> 00:20:24.839
I can add a custom URL like HospitalStreamlitApp and save.

00:20:24.839 --> 00:20:29.280
That's a URL that I would share with others if they want to check it out.

00:20:29.280 --> 00:20:33.239
If I want to see what it actually looks like when I share it with someone, I can click

00:20:33.239 --> 00:20:35.959
Open Solo.

00:20:35.959 --> 00:20:40.920
With that, I hope that this video gave a nice overview of different features that you can

00:20:40.920 --> 00:20:45.359
use within Positron when you develop your next Streamlit app.

00:20:45.359 --> 00:20:50.880
Check out positron.posit.co for instructions and the download link.

00:20:50.880 --> 00:20:53.079
I'm really excited to see what you create.

00:20:53.079 --> 00:20:53.479
Thanks.

